        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP attributes</strong> are descriptive tags you enable on your Google Business Profile that tell searchers specific details about your business — <strong>accessibility features, payment methods, service options, and identity attributes</strong> like women-owned or LGBTQ+ friendly. Google offers two types: factual attributes set by the owner and subjective attributes crowdsourced from customers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Platform</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Google Business Profile</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Interaction lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+70%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local businesses set their category and stop. GBP attributes are the second layer — the fine-grained signals that unlock filtered searches, appointment buttons, and identity discovery. Ten minutes to enable, months of extra visibility.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are GBP attributes?</h2>
        <p>GBP attributes are structured tags that highlight specific qualities of a business on Google Business Profile. A restaurant might display outdoor seating and delivery. A law office might show online appointments and wheelchair accessibility. A café might tag itself as women-owned and LGBTQ+ friendly.</p>
        <p>Available attributes are determined by your primary category, which is why picking the right primary category matters — it unlocks the attribute set you can use.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google\u2019s data on completeness</div>
          <p>According to Google, <strong>businesses with complete attribute profiles get 70% more interactions</strong> than those without. Attributes power filtered search, voice search, and features like appointment booking — turning a passive listing into a discoverable one.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP attributes matter</h2>
        <p>Four reasons attributes deserve a spot on your local SEO checklist:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>They enable filtered searches.</strong> A user filtering Google Maps for "wheelchair accessible" or "outdoor seating" only sees businesses with those attributes set. No attribute, no visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>They improve relevance for specific queries.</strong> Attributes act as extra semantic signal for queries like "vegan restaurant near me" or "coffee shop with free wifi".</li>
          <li><strong>They build trust through identity attributes.</strong> Identity attributes (women-owned, veteran-owned, LGBTQ+ friendly, Black-owned) surface prominently on the listing and drive click-through from users looking to support specific communities.</li>
          <li><strong>They unlock GBP features.</strong> The "online appointments" attribute, for example, triggers Google\u2019s appointment booking integration — a button on the listing that turns discovery into a booked slot.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP attributes work</h2>
        <p>Two systems, one profile. Owners control factual attributes. Customers vote on subjective ones.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Setting factual attributes as the owner</span><br>
          Business Profile <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Edit profile <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> More<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Enable: <span class="uf-new">Wheelchair accessible entrance</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Enable: <span class="uf-new">Free Wi-Fi</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Enable: <span class="uf-new">Online appointments</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Attributes appear on the public listing within minutes</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Factual attributes</h3>
        <p>Set by the business owner in the GBP dashboard. Examples: wheelchair accessibility, free parking, online appointments, curbside pickup, accepts credit cards. Owners have full control over these.</p>

        <h3>Subjective attributes</h3>
        <p>Crowdsourced from customer responses to Google\u2019s "Know this place?" prompts. Examples: cozy, romantic, good for kids, quiet, casual. Owners cannot directly edit subjective attributes — they emerge from real customer feedback.</p>

        <h3>Identity attributes</h3>
        <p>A subset of factual attributes that highlight ownership or identity. Examples: women-owned, veteran-owned, LGBTQ+ friendly, Black-owned, Latino-owned, Asian-owned. These render as visible badges on the listing.</p>

