          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Appointment requests up <span class="uf-new">25%</span> in a quarter<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># The attribute unlocked a UI feature, not just metadata</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP attributes vs GBP categories — which does what</h2>
        <p>Both are structured metadata on your Business Profile. They solve different jobs.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Categories tell Google</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>What your business fundamentally does</li>
              <li>Which core searches you should appear for</li>
              <li>Which UI features to expose on the listing</li>
              <li>Which attribute set you can pick from</li>
              <li>Which competitors you rank against</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Attributes tell searchers</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Specific features they filter for</li>
              <li>Whether accessibility needs are met</li>
              <li>How they can pay and get served</li>
              <li>Identity signals they care about</li>
              <li>What experience to expect (subjective tags)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP attributes</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Enable every applicable attribute.</strong> Incomplete attribute profiles miss filtered searches. If it applies to your business, turn it on.</li>
          <li><strong>Start with accessibility, then service options, then identity.</strong> These have the biggest impact on filtered searches and trust signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Match your website content to your attributes.</strong> If you claim "outdoor seating", your website should show it. Google cross-checks entity signals across surfaces.</li>
          <li><strong>Review quarterly.</strong> Google adds new attributes throughout the year — new identity attributes, new payment methods, new service options. Old profiles fall behind.</li>
          <li><strong>Never claim an attribute you cannot honour.</strong> A business claiming "wheelchair accessible" that is not accessible will get flagged in reviews and can lose GBP trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Use identity attributes if they apply.</strong> Women-owned, veteran-owned, and LGBTQ+ friendly badges drive click-through from users specifically looking to support those businesses.</li>
          <li><strong>Encourage genuine reviews to shape subjective attributes.</strong> "Good for kids" or "romantic" show up when enough customers describe your business that way in reviews.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — leaving default attributes empty</div>
          <p>The GBP dashboard hides attributes behind the "More" or "Edit profile" menu. Owners assume they are optional and skip them. Result: their listing never appears in filtered searches and never gets booking buttons. This is the single most common local SEO miss for small businesses.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP attribute mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skipping the attribute section</strong> — the number-one cause of missed filtered-search visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Claiming attributes you cannot deliver</strong> — customers will call it out in reviews and Google will trust your listing less.</li>
          <li><strong>Not reviewing quarterly</strong> — new attributes are added constantly; old profiles miss them.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring identity attributes</strong> — these are the only badges visible directly on the listing and drive real click-through.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming subjective attributes can be edited</strong> — they can\u2019t. Only real customer feedback moves them.</li>
        </ul>

